\par 
\par On August 26, 2006, the SCV Historical Society hosted a lecture program on }{\b\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281 The History of Movie Making in the Santa Clarita Valley.}{\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281 
  The guest speaker was Marc Wanamaker, an acknowledged and respected archivist/historian of the movie industry.  
\par 
\par I have known Marc since 1998, when he explained to me that our patron, Bill, had never occupied t
he William S. Hart building on the Paramount Studio Lot.  Years earlier, the Studio had asked Marc for a list of famous stars after which they could name each building, for Public Relations purposes.  I prevailed upon Marc to write an article for the }{
\b\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281 Hart Of The Matter }{\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281 newsletter which I edited at the time.  I am enclosing a copy of his article that was featured in our September 1998 issue.
\par 
\par Incidentally, Marc is the co-author of a series of }{\b\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281 Picture Books}{\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281  about our Southern California areas.  }{\b\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281 Los Angeles - 
Past & Present, Hollywood - Past & Present, Orange County - Past & Present, and San Diego - Past & Present.  }{\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281 I have a copy of }{\b\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281 Los Angeles - Past & Present }{\f1\fs20\insrsid6821281 
and give it my heartiest endorsement.  Marc has selected about 60 photographs of historical sites in 
the Greater LA area, some dating back to 1880 through 1930.  Then, his co-author, photographer George Jezak, set up his camera at he same spot and took a picture as it looks today.  Marc captioned each photo with a short story about the changes.  
\par 
